aa(lp128
VAnd why does exchange raise living standards?
p129
aVWell, the answer came from David Ricardo in 1817.
p130
aVAnd here is a Stone Age version of his story,
p131
aValthough he told it in terms of trade between countries.
p132
aVAdam takes four hours to make a spear and three hours to make an axe.
p133
aVOz takes one hour to make a spear and two hours to make an axe.
p134
aVSo Oz is better at both spears and axes than Adam.
p135
aVHe doesn't need Adam.
p136
aVHe can make his own spears and axes.
p137
aVWell no, because if you think about it,
p138
aVif Oz makes two spears and Adam make two axes,
p139
aVand then they trade,
p140
aVthen they will each have saved an hour of work.
p141
aVAnd the more they do this, the more true it's going to be,
p142
aVbecause the more they do this, the better Adam is going to get at making axes
p143
aVand the better Oz is going to get at making spears.
p144
aVSo the gains from trade are only going to grow.
p145
aVAnd this is one of the beauties of exchange,
p146
aVis it actually creates the momentum
p147
aVfor more specialization,
p148
aVwhich creates the momentum for more exchange and so on.
p149
aVAdam and Oz both saved an hour of time.
p150
aVThat is prosperity, the saving of time
p151
aVin satisfying your needs.
